            <h3>Scope</h3>
            <p>In Java, a scope defines the region of code where a variable or method is accessible. There are mainly three types of scopes</p>
            <ol>
                <li><h4>Local scope:</h4>Variables declared within a block of code, such as within a method or a loop, have local scope. They are only accessible within that specific block.</p></li>
                <li><h4>Instance scope:</h4><p>Variables declared within a class but outside any methods have instance scope. They are associated with instances (objects) of the class and can be accessed by methods within the same class.</p></li>
                <li><h4>Class scope:</h4><p>Variables declared as static within a class have class scope. They are shared among all instances of the class and can be accessed using the class name.</p></li>
            </ol>
            
            <div class="code_container">
                <div class="code_wrapper">
                    <pre>
                        <code id="code" class="language-Java">
                            public class MyClass {
                                // This is a class-level variable with class-wide scope
                                  static int classVariable = 10;
                                public static void main(String args[]) {
                                
                             
                                    // This is a method-level variable with method-wide scope
                                    int methodVariable = 5;
                            
                                    System.out.println("Inside the main method:");
                                    System.out.println("classVariable: " + classVariable);
                                    System.out.println("methodVariable: " + methodVariable);
                            
                                    if (true) {
                                        // This is a block-level variable with block-wide scope (inside the if block)
                                        int blockVariable = 15;
                            
                                        System.out.println("Inside the if block:");
                                        System.out.println("classVariable: " + classVariable);
                                        System.out.println("methodVariable: " + methodVariable);
                                        System.out.println("blockVariable: " + blockVariable);
                                    }
                            
                                    // The blockVariable is not accessible here because it's out of scope
                                    // System.out.println("Outside the if block:");
                                    // System.out.println("blockVariable: " + blockVariable);
                            
                                    // You can still access classVariable and methodVariable here
                                    System.out.println("Outside the if block:");
                                    System.out.println("classVariable: " + classVariable);
                                    System.out.println("methodVariable: " + methodVariable);
                                }
                            }
                        </code>
